  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Firm-level demonstration of technologies and productivity enhancement for the pulp and paper industry</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As of today, the Indian paper industry is unable to meet the growing market demands due to low productivity, which in turn is the result of several challenges such as weak pace of innovation, scarce availability of raw materials, high cost of basic inputs, low economies of scale and use of outdated technology in a majority of firms. There is thus a latent but urgent need to technologically upgrade Indian paper mills to improve their productivity and sustainability. In order to address the aforementioned, on 31 March 2018, UNIDO, with the aid of the International Centre for Inclusive and Sustainable Industrial Development, operationally completed the project &#x201C;Development and adoption of appropriate technologies for enhancing productivity in the paper and pulp sector&#x201D; (SAP ID: 150282. &#x2018;Phase-1 Project). The project&#x2019;s independent terminal evaluation confirmed that the project had strengthened management and technological capacity and capability of the nodal technical institution for the Indian paper and pulp industry, respectively the Central Pulp and Paper Research Institute (CPPRI) and select industry associations. These are now in better position to provide technical and management support to the Indian pulp and paper industry. The proposed project &#x2018;Firm-level demonstration of technologies and productivity enhancement for the pulp and paper industry (Paper Project Phase-2)&#x2019; therefore envisages to demonstrate (on a pilot scale at mill level, at multiple locations across the country) two technologies (membrane filtration and liquor heat treatment), along with the development of the requisite capacity and process improvement interventions. This will facilitate technology uptake and firm level innovation leading to increased productivity and competitiveness. Utilizing a system of innovation approach is crucial to the successful uptake of these technological solutions by industry and is explained in further detail as a part of the UNIDO approach. The funds for the project will be from the IDF contribution made by the Government of India. In addition this will be supplemented by an in- kind contribution from industry.</narrative>
  </description>
